<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <%- include('partials/head') %>

  <body>
    <%- include('partials/nav') %>

   <main>
      <section class="food-support-hero">
        <h1>Waste Management in Ladywood</h1>
        <p>Understanding the waste challenges facing Birmingham and what is being done to address them.</p>
      </section>

       <section class="food-support-cta">
        <h2>Find waste and recycling services near you</h2>
        <p>Browse waste and recycling services listed in the CommunityLink directory.</p>
        <a href="/services" class="btn-services">View Waste Services</a>
      </section>


      <section class="food-info">

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Birmingham's Waste Problem</h2>
          <p>
            In 2021, Birmingham generated an estimated 2.8 million tonnes of waste, made up of
            hazardous, municipal, commercial, industrial, and construction and demolition waste.
            Approximately 20% of the total waste generated was sent to landfill, with nearly half
            originating from construction and demolition. Birmingham's recycling rate of 22% is
            the worst in the West Midlands, and has barely changed in a decade — it stood at
            22.9% in 2015/16 and 22.7% in 2023/24, compared to 42.3% across England.
          </p>
          <p>
            Much of Birmingham's recycling is exported internationally — in 2020, 39% was sent
            to Turkey, 12% to Malaysia and 7% to Poland. Birmingham's contaminated recycling
            (waste sent to recycling that cannot actually be recycled) is also higher than the
            national average at 9.9% compared to 5.8% nationally.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Waste in Ladywood</h2>
          <p>
            Terraced cottages around Ladywood, originally built for working-class labourers, are
            very small with little room for bins. Each week residents put their bins on the street,
            blocking pavements. Some terraced houses have no access to bins at all and use bags,
            which waste collectors are not always aware of — leading to a build-up of waste and
            fly-tipping on streets. Waste can also end up in waterways and canals, destroying
            vegetation and wildlife.
          </p>
          <p>
            Lower income inner city areas, including Ladywood, are impacted to a greater extent
            by waste build-up compared to more affluent areas. Birmingham City Council declared
            a major incident in March 2025 to tackle 17,000 tonnes of uncollected waste,
            increasing street cleaning and fly-tip removal across the city.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>The Bin Strikes</h2>
          <p>
            In January 2025, a dispute between trade union Unite and Birmingham City Council
            broke out over pay cuts and the elimination of Waste Recycling and Collection Officer
            roles as part of the council's budget cuts. An indefinite all-out strike began on
            11 March 2025. Large amounts of waste built up on the streets and major queues formed
            at mobile collection points, leading to wider concerns over public health and
            breeding grounds for rats. In April, the UK government called in Army specialists to
            provide logistical and planning support.
          </p>
          <p>
            A similar strike occurred in 2017 for seven weeks due to proposed job losses and
            wage decreases under Birmingham City Council's restructuring plans. These disputes
            highlight the impact that austerity and budget cuts have on essential public services
            in areas like Ladywood.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>How Waste is Managed</h2>
          <p>
            Veolia, in partnership with Birmingham City Council, manages the city's refuse
            treatment, dry mixed recycling, household recycling centres, waste transfer stations
            and green recycling. 500,000 tonnes of municipal waste is managed by the council
            each year. The city's Energy Recovery Facility in Tyseley takes 350,000 tonnes of
            Birmingham's rubbish each year and converts it into electricity for up to 63,000
            homes. The facility is designed to treat waste that cannot be reused, recycled or
            composted.
          </p>
          <p>
            There are five Household Recycling Centres in Birmingham, but all are only accessible
            by vehicle and located between a 25 and 41 minute drive from Ladywood. Birmingham
            City Council has removed street recycling banks due to fly-tipping. Mobile Household
            Waste Centres visit areas across Birmingham each week for residents to dispose of
            general household and bulky waste items.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="food-info-block">
          <h2>Waste as a Resource</h2>
          <p>
            Birmingham has goals of becoming a zero waste to landfill city by 2040, with a target
            recycling rate of 40% by 2026, rising to 70% by 2040. The circular economy approach
            focuses on eliminating waste and pollution, keeping products and materials in use, and
            regenerating nature. Community organisations like Generous Waste run workshops to
            change the perception of waste — seeing it not as something to discard, but as a
            material with value and potential.
          </p>
          <p>
            Repair cafes have been growing across the city, keeping valuable items out of landfill
            while building community skills and connections. CIVIC SQUARE is also exploring how
            waste streams in Ladywood can be incorporated into their Neighbourhood Microfactory,
            supporting a shift from a throwaway culture towards repair and reuse.
          </p>
        </div>

      </section>

     
    </main>

    <%- include('partials/footer') %>
  </body>
</html>
